**Define:** Clearly articulate the problem or opportunity that needs to be addressed.


I. Introduction

-   Overview of the design thinking process
-   Importance of the "define" step in design thinking

II. Understanding the problem

-   Techniques for identifying and defining the problem or opportunity (e.g. user research, stakeholder interviews, focus groups)
-   How to create a problem statement that is clear, concise and actionable

III. Identifying user needs

-   How to gather information about user needs, wants, and limitations
-   How to create user personas and empathy maps

IV. Defining the design challenge

-   How to translate user needs and problem statement into a design challenge
-   How to create a point of view (POV) statement that guides the design process

V. Defining success criteria

-   How to create measurable and actionable success criteria for the design
-   How to use success criteria to evaluate and iterate on the design

VI. Conclusion

-   Recap of key points
-   Discussion of the ongoing importance of defining the problem and user needs in the design thinking process
-   Encourage audience to practice the skills and methods presented in the lecture in their own design work.



